{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3565f5c7-2f92-4a73-ab9c-87ecfa360915","content":"\n\nHere's what to change:\n\n1. **Update the test adapter** — replace `NUnit3TestAdapter` with the new one:\n   ```xml\n   <!-- Remove -->\n   <PackageReference Include=\"NUnit3TestAdapter\" Version=\"4.6.0\" />\n\n   <!-- Add -->\n   <PackageReference Include=\"NUnit.Testing.Extensions.Microsoft.Testing.Platform\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n   ```\n\n2. **Enable the new platform** in your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n     <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n3. **Keep** `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk` — it's still needed.\n\n4. **Run tests** with:\n   ```bash\n   dotnet test\n   # or run the test executable directly:\n   dotnet run --project YourTests.csproj\n   ```\n\n**Key notes:**\n- The `EnableMSTestRunner` property name applies to all frameworks (not just MSTest) when using Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n- Setting `OutputType` to `Exe` is required because tests now run as a standalone executable.\n- If you use `dotnet test`, it auto-detects the new platform. You can also pass `--` to forward args to the test host (e.g., `dotnet test -- --filter \"Name=MyTest\"`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"82d575dc-e318-4d7c-9126-e2214f59d076","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating an NUnit test project from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. This is a knowledge question - I don't need to explore any codebase. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":407},"id":"805c3c62-48d2-4c6e-9366-93d2e44f964b","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:41:52.121Z","parentId":"ccb9f137-7272-4d55-b2d7-f7c779ac44a6"}
